## Anti-Patterns

<!-- WHY: D2 requires 5+ anti-patterns with prevention. Systems have composition-specific failure modes. -->
<!-- WHY: These are different from squad anti-patterns — the failures here are architectural, not coordination. -->

| Pattern | Why It Fails | Prevention |
|---------|-------------|------------|
| Components that call each other circularly | Infinite loop or deadlock with no exit | Define a directed acyclic graph (DAG) for all component interactions |
| Routing by trial-and-error | System tries components until one "works" — unpredictable and slow | Every intent must map to exactly one deterministic path |
| Shared mutable state without locking | Two components overwrite each other's output | Route through a single output component; never let two write simultaneously |
| Treating the system as a monolith | Creator updates one component without checking others | Each component change triggers a cross-system integration check |
| Undeclared component dependencies | Component A silently requires B's output without a defined contract | All inter-component dependencies must be listed in Component Inventory |

